node.text: The Fifty returns for 2021. Despite the challenges of a low snow year, a record breaking avalanche year, the lingering effects of a global pandemic and a closed border between Canada and the US, the winter of 2021 had its successes. From Montana to Alaska, Colorado to California, the third year of The Fifty bring some amazing stories, the requisite amount of suffering, some laughs and some good ole backcountry education alongside some the best mountain athletes in the world. All episodes coming out in Fall 2021.

node.text: Happy dang birthday to this queen, ski goddess and soon to be mom @elysesaugstad! We've been through a lot of cool stuff together, from skiing in the raddest of places to the day to day 'monotony' that is more enjoyable because of you, but this next journey you're on, the one of you becoming a mom, well that's the one I'm most impressed with. Happy birthday my love.

node.text: Little known fact, I was a linguistics major in college. With that, you study semantics, aka, the meaning of words. One of the unique things I remember from those classes is how fluid word meaning is and how individual perspective walled by time, environment and up bringing can create wildly different interpretations of universal words. Hence why many people will find the "Squaw" word non-offensive and a term that they associate with joy. It's also why many others, find it wildly degrading, unwelcoming and offensive. So personally I don't care what your thoughts are about the meaning of that term because it's been shaped by your individual perspective. Today, the only thing that matters is the meaning that we give to @palisadestahoe . If we center it around the joy of sliding down the most fun ski area on earth, the wildly creative, diehard and talented skiers / snowboarders that call the mountain home and the community that cherishes this place, then the meaning of what is special about this place will never die. It's up to you to create that meaning.

node.text:
Hardcore climbers call this act "Scrambling". Many others call it "Free Solo-ing". I call it "Being scared for a couple hours climbing with no ropes over a thousand feet of exposure but getting your shit together, focusing on the rock in front of you and having a hell of an adventure climbing up a mountain". I have a feeling the third name will stick one day. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Just got back from one hell of a fun / adrenaline inducing / exhausting weekend mission in the High Sierra with @nick_russelll and @forrestshearer 
⁠⁠
@mammutna @salomon @swatch ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
